RØDD — Swedish for simply "row", or the act of rowing — is a personal R&D project born from one precise goal: to make a consumer Bluetooth rowing machine talk to iOS cleanly and without friction.

The project came out of a gap in the market: unable to find any fitness app I was happy with, I set out to build a clean, rigorous and technically sharp interface. As a developer, this project is my lab for putting a complete design cycle through its paces, solo — from the reverse-engineering phase all the way to a robust software architecture.

## The technical pivot

My first instinct was React Native, to iterate fast. But from the very first proof of concept, the technical constraints brought me back to earth. To cleanly handle continuous hardware communication with `CoreBluetooth` and data export to `Apple HealthKit`, cross-platform was showing its limits. Swift imposed itself — not as an ideal preference, but as the logical choice for this specific use case.

## Build methodology & R&D timeline

Once native was settled, development followed a very linear path, immediately confronting the theory of the code with the constraints of the hardware:

1. **Initial reverse-engineering.** Before writing a single line of Swift, I analysed the rower's payloads. By sniffing the raw Bluetooth frames with the nRF Connect app, I confirmed the signal existed and mapped the machine's characteristics.
2. **System bring-up.** Once the protocol was understood, I implemented the `CoreBluetooth` layer to instantiate the peripheral manager and cleanly handle iOS's first access-permission prompts.
3. **Physical crash-test.** I then built a raw scanner and a bare-bones interface to pair the iPhone with the rower and observe the data stream under real effort.

It was during those first sessions that the reality of the hardware caught up with the theory. Behind the FTMS standard (Fitness Machine Service), the machine's firmware sometimes returns inconsistent raw values that have to be intercepted and corrected. Concretely, you read the frame byte by byte: two *flag* bytes announce which fields are present, then comes the Stroke Rate — encoded in half-units, hence the division by 2 — and the rest depending on the bits. Here is an excerpt from my FTMS parser:

```swift
/// FTMS Rower Data parser (characteristic 2AD1).
enum FtmsParser {
    static func parseRowerData(_ data: Data) -> LiveMetrics? {
        guard data.count >= 2 else { return nil }

        // 2 flag bytes (little-endian): they tell which fields follow.
        let flags = UInt16(data[0]) | (UInt16(data[1]) << 8)
        var offset = 2

        // Stroke Rate (UInt8 / 2) + Stroke Count (UInt16) — always present.
        guard let strokeRateRaw = readUInt8(data, at: &offset),
              let strokeCountRaw = readUInt16(data, at: &offset) else { return nil }
        let strokeRate = clampStrokeRate(Double(strokeRateRaw) / 2.0)

        // … then distance, pace, power… depending on the flag bits.
    }
}
```

The `clampStrokeRate` is not incidental: it is the first guardrail against a firmware that, sometimes, talks nonsense. I will come back to it in detail in a future article.

